We recommended to the management to perform the following procedures:

1)	The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to effect disbursement voucher and Journal Entry Voucher (JEV), respectively, to revert such amount back to the general fund, duly supported with evidential document/s;

2)	The Municipal Budget Officer to include such amount in the determination of surplus during the year, subject for subsequent enactment; 

3)  The Sangguniang Bayan to amend the provision set under Section 4 of the Municipal Ordinance No. 21, series of 2017, to be consistent with Sections 309 and 322 of RA 7160 and to New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual for LGUs;

4)	The management to submit the foregoing documents to the audit team for our further evaluation; and,

Stop, henceforth, the improper practice of transferring unused local funds from general to trust fund without anchoring any law, rule or regulation authorizing the same.

We recommended to the officials of the Municipal Government of Pangantucan and Employees’ Union to submit the following lacking documents, subject for our further review and evaluation:

Copy of the CNA signed by both parties;

Resolution duly signed by said parties and duly approved by the Agency Head, incorporating therein the guidelines on the grant of CNA Incentive, such as: (i) the specific criteria for determining who are entitled; and (ii) the distribution of the amount available and the rate of the CNA incentive; 

Certificate issued by the Head of Agency supported with evidential documents showing that the LGU generated savings from the allowable MOOE allotments as a result of cost-cutting measures and joint efforts of management and employees; and,

4) 	Proof that the LGU has accomplished, as of September 30, 2020, at least an average of 70% of all the targets under the programs/activities/projects approved in the LGU budget for FY 2020

We recommended to the management to immediately refund the unutilized fund of the Emergency Subsidy Program downloaded by DSWD Field Office No. 10, amounting to P24,000.00.

Further, organize a validation committee who will work in close coordination with barangay officials concerned and the MSWDO to conduct verification if the eligibility requirements are met by said 140 beneficiaries and direct the committee to submit to the audit team a report/status of their verification and the actions taken by management;

Furthermore, required the MSWDO and the Municipal Accountant to obtain and submit immediately to audit team the “certified list” from DSWD Field Office 10 and the noted lacking documentary requirements saved in compact disc (CD) copy (considering the voluminous documents involved) for the continuance of our audit.

